##The boiling hot pot market, meet the epidemic ice

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

In the news of a restaurant industry that has taken a beating, there are usually two voices. One encourages the shopkeepers to hang on a little longer, the other worries, "fruit and vegetables are so expensive these days, some people don't pay their salaries during the quarantine, and how long can there be retaliatory spending? "? My hands are so tight that I don't dare to spend any more money. "

Ms Agnes Sze ching-wai

Editor | Xiao Zhu

"Oh, no. Every cow needs to be skinny every day. "

Bianca Wu remembers her last hot pot meal so far.

It was January 16th, and at the time, new cap pneumonia was a distant term, masks were not yet popular, and people in the streets and alleys were still breathing in their mouths, sichuan-chongqing hot pot, old Beijing instant-boiled mutton, Chaoshan beef pot, coconut chicken hot pot are everywhere in Chaoyang District.

In the run up to the Spring Festival, Bianca Wu's hot pot meal was dominated by vegetarian dishes. For several nights in the month that followed, she looked at the ceiling and saw a scene that was played over and over: the Red Oil boiling in the Jiugongge, the hairy belly rolling, the dip in her mouth just as it was being cooked. Zoom in, and you can see the garlic puree in the dip. Zoom out, the whole table also yellow throat, meat, bean skin, potatoes..

Bianca Wu isn't the only one who wants to eat hot pot but can't. Fried Chicken, milk tea and hot pot are the most popular foods after the outbreak ended, according to the popular micro blog. The first two fumble with the recipe, can roughly restore the taste of the outside, only hot pot, almost no difficulty in operation, but the most difficult to copy and friends in hot pot restaurant instant-boiled meat feeling. Sometimes, getting together to eat and talk, enjoy a high level of service, and watch ramen shows is just as important as eating.

Hotpot owners'business has taken a bigger hit this month as the restaurant industry has generally taken a beating than the desire of hotpot lovers.

Li Xiang is the manager of a branch of Chongqing Base area chain hotpot restaurant. He has been worried ever since he closed for the holiday on December twenty-nine. When he was in his 30s, he found that the epidemic was getting worse and worse. The streets were deserted except for supermarkets and pharmacies that remained open. "

Like most restaurants, Li Xiang's hot pot restaurant has the highest annual traffic and turnover during the Spring Festival. Chongqing People's family dinner and friends get together, mostly choose in hot pot restaurant. In previous years, Li's stores sold more than 200,000 units during the seven-day Golden Week holiday, five times more than on a typical weekday. Without the outbreak, he expects sales of 400,000 to 500,000 this year.

On January 30, he went to the store with some of his employees to get the ingredients. They took stock of the food, divided it up, set up a stall in front of the store, and sold it to passersby below cost. Li calculates that it would be worth as much as $20,000 if it were not.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Many hotpot restaurants choose to sell their dishes directly to cut their losses

As branch store manager, Li Xiang only has to worry about the profit and loss of his own store. He does not understand the concept of cash flow, nor is he concerned about the direction of the entire hotpot industry. What worries him is the current situation, and the long tail that will follow in the months to come. His hotpot restaurant has more than 40 tables, and at peak times, customers have to wait in line for an hour. Unless the epidemic is completely over, he thought, the dinners would be dangerous and no guests would come.

But for Lin Haiping, founder of beef hotpot in Shantou's Bahe Caspian Sea, there are far more problems.

Lin, who owns 132 chain stores, has divided his response to the outbreak into three steps: "Safety, " "stop" and "increase revenue. " Four branches in Wuhan are still in the first phase. In the more than a month since the suspension began, hundreds of Baheli stores have lost 60 million yuan. The cash flow will last about two months, and if the situation does not improve by the third month, Lin is prepared to sell his property.

Of the $60m in losses, two thirds are hard losses, such as rent, labor and dorm costs. And shops supporting the farm, slaughterhouse and central kitchen also closed, is a large sum of money. He also loved his cows -- as if they had been transported to the slaughterhouse years ago because of poor logistics during the Spring Festival. The fatter the cows were, the better. The two most popular parts were the chest and the toes. Now, after a month or so of living in a slaughterhouse that hasn't been fully restored, "every cow has to be lean every day. ". "

It's more of an invisible drain. Some are still working on it, because this outbreak, it's over. " That is to say, some of the branches were in a bad state of operation. They had hoped to take advantage of the Spring Festival rush to save them. However, the boiling hot pot market was hit by an epidemic of ice-cold weather. All of them lost money and were "a little weak" . The "chicken ribs" stores were among the first to be stopped, not just "closed, " but completely closed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the Bahe Caspian Sea official notice, the larger stores used the word "closed, " and some used the word "closed. "

A desperate attempt to save his own skin

When he was hungry, Bianca Wu thought about making hotpot at home. She did the math: If the family stock of food used to rinse hot pot, a meal or two to eat up, if cooked into stir-fry, penny-pinching, can last a week. She also thought about buying hot pot, but after a group of nearly 300 people asked questions, everyone who had bought a hot pot told her "not good. ".

The hot pot market has exploded since 2017, expanding rapidly to nearly 10 billion levels in three years. From New Year's Eve in 2020 to the ninth day of the Lunar New Year, the turnover of convenience food represented by hot pot in JD.com increased 3.5 times, while sales of hot pot in suning increased 370.27 percent year-on-year, according to data from the e-commerce platform, sales of spicy beef from hot pot alone have topped 10,000,25,000 and 30,000 since this month, according to Xiaolongkan, the company's flagship tmall stores, and Haidilao.

Li's hot pot restaurant also tried to keep up with the trend by offering its own hot pot around 2018. R & D and Publicity combined, that's one million grand.

However, since the hot pot market is similar to the traditional fast food market, consumers will instinctively trust the brands associated with fast food companies, or the nationwide distribution of catering enterprises, such as the national chain Haidilao and Xiaolongkan. Li's hotpot restaurant, a local brand in Chongqing, has not broken through, though it has branches in Sichuan, Shandong, Henan and Guizhou.

Finally, after only half a year, just developed from the hot pot stopped production, just up and running Taobao shop followed.

There is also a third option, hot pot takeout, between making do with the hot pot and not having it.

Before the outbreak, hotpot takeout was a source of extra revenue for some chain hotpot stores. According to Meituan Dianping in 2019 launched the "China catering report" shows that the development of the hot pot delivery market attention. Shabu, which serves one person hot pot, aggressively promoted takeout in the first half of 2018, with revenue up 120 per cent year-on-year. Haidilao, which has long had to wait in line, has launched a store run by a separate department that delivers only to customers. From 2017 to 2019, take-out orders and sales rose 47.9 percent and 40.9 percent, respectively, according to Haidilao's results.

However, some for the quality of food or restaurant scene requirements of the boss, is not happy to open the delivery business. Lin Haiping is one of them. Chaoshan beef hotpot requires a high quality of meat. Many of the major overseas chain beef hotpot restaurants have their own slaughterhouses, supply chains and central kitchens to ensure that the meat is as fresh as possible. In the case of Baheli, a cow can not be slaughtered and eaten for more than six hours. As a result, although takeout has long been available in Baheli, only staples such as Char kway teow are served.

There are two main types of hot pot takeout, one will be hot hot pot ingredients, and then distribution to customers, such as Xiabu feeding and Jingge. The other provides rental and recycling services for boilers and pans, such as Haidilao. Lin had not looked at the take-out market before. During this period, he studied it and found that some take-out food was over-packaged and some used recycling facilities such as boiler leasing, but "the cost was too high, the cost is always passed on to the customer.". Some hotpot shops, will assign staff to guests home hot pot, "an unknown person, he is always there, or sit together to eat it, in the side to see, I feel uncomfortable. ". "He thought it was a little odd.

In the restaurant industry, hotpot is a special case, it contains the offline social attributes, the value-added services are also greater. "hotpot is a popular choice for dining out, with more than half of consumers choosing hotpot, with 10% to 30% of the total number of times they go out for dinner, " said the report, "Hot Pot Industry Research and Consumer Research" , released late last year, and with 70-130 yuan in high-grade chafing dish mostly. In the perception of the public, the choice of the medium and high end is related to the services they provide.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Many hotpot restaurants famous for their service often bring special performances to the diners

Take-away pot bottoms and dishes, which many hotpot restaurants never thought of before the onslaught of the epidemic, are now chosen out of desperation to save themselves.

On February 10th Bahe Caspian began to offer takeout after continuing to lose money. As the central kitchen has not yet returned to work, those who opened the take-out business, had to be the store staff beat beef balls. Lin Haiping a bit helpless, because this will lead to each store on the taste of beef balls slightly different. He also worries that the taste and experience of freshly cut beef will be greatly affected if it is not eaten as soon as it is served.

Temporary entry, drive ducks on the shelves, many hot pot takeaway can only have mouth, if the real dining experience, can not be compared with the canteen. The takeaway packages available in Baheli are simple, disposable plastic boxes with a lettuce leaf at the bottom. Real-time activity on social networks also shows that Baheli's deliveries are losing potential customers by not offering induction cookers and one-person meal packages.

In addition, take-out how to ensure the freshness of the ingredients, is also the new business owners need to address the problem. On Zhihu, someone asked, "is it safe to order takeout at home during a new outbreak of coronary pneumonia? "? Is it okay to order takeout during an outbreak? "I ordered pork and pickled cabbage pan-fried last night. The meat is pink and purple. Is it undercooked? I woke up this morning with an uncomfortable chest. Now it's low heat. I haven't been out in two days. Please don't order takeout... "

The new coronavirus contact mode of transmission, but also let consumers on the point of delivery this matter, has never been able to do the old trust. Even as delivery platforms and self-delivered food brands launch "contactless delivery, " fear of the virus is likely to make takeaways less appealing -- as is the daily call for beef fondue on Florida's social media platform, after the launch of takeaway in Baheli, the average sales volume is only 30% of that in the canteen.

30% is a rare number. This may be due to Chaoshan hotpot's unique cutting method for beef, which leaves Chaoshan where consumers have to go to beef hotpot shops to buy raw meat cut this way. In this epidemic, this characteristic is more obvious: if you want to eat Sichuan and Chongqing Hotpot, old Beijing hot boiled mutton, northeast pickled cabbage pot, even pig belly chicken, coconut chicken, fresh e-commerce platform is likely to meet demand. Only beef hotpot, can only count on the shop to open take-out.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Some hotpot restaurants that are heavily influenced by the quality of the meat offer special windows for diners to take their meals instead of takeout

I'll lose everything

There is no business to do, but Li Xiang's hot pot restaurant has yet to open a take-out service. "there are so many hotpot restaurants in Chongqing, " he said. "There are almost all of them downstairs. Hot Pot takeout at home, cooking it yourself, it's a lot of work. "

Contrary to his judgment, hot pot hungry Chongqing people have been holding back for nearly a month, has begun to hot pot delivery of retaliatory consumption. As of Feb. 20, a total of 72 hotpot restaurants in Chongqing had opened contactless delivery services, with three-day sales totaling more than 10,000 units and a total sales of nearly 3 million units, China News Service reported on Feb. 21. Orders are usually placed early in the morning and in the middle of the night, when Bianca Wu is staring up at the ceiling.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
According to statistics, hot pot enterprises continue to provide contactless take-out, Chongqing people ordered 10,000 single hot pot takeout figure source China News Network

According to industry analyst Liu Yuenan, hotels and restaurants will be the first industry to recover after the outbreak is brought under control, followed by tourism. "service consumption has become a critical need, and there will be a retaliatory rebound after its suppression. The consumption of the restaurant industry immediate strong, retaliatory rebound slightly limited, but just need properties, demand will quickly return to normal. "

Pocket tightening is not only the consumer, Lin Haiping is also aware of the Hubei region outside, his hot pot restaurant must quickly enter the "revenue" link. The delivery business that had to be done opened the door to a new world for him, and he decided to wait for the canteen to resume, the delivery will continue. He calculated that even if the take-out sales were only one-third of what they are now, it would still be an extra 10% of revenue. "

You see the best, you have to prepare for the worst. It's the entire restaurant industry that has been hit hard by this outbreak. According to data released by the National Bureau of Statistics of the People's Republic of China, more than 15 percent of the country's total restaurant revenue last year came from the Spring Festival. This year, as a result of the special situation of the new crown epidemic, nearly 80% of the restaurant business revenue loss of more than 100% . Even the head of a restaurant brand, such as Haidilao, which has gone public, has suffered more than $5 billion in losses from the suspension of its mainland stores.

The worst Li could think of would be to sell the shop. In 2013, he took over from his father the hotpot restaurant, which had been in operation in Nanping for more than a decade. Over the next seven years, he saw a decline in business due to the opening of branches and the impact of big brands. "The restaurant business must have gone from boom to bust, " he says. "

He is not worried about a lack of takers, and agrees with the Survival of the fittest's brutal rules. "This is a market where the big fish eat the little fish, and when the little fish don't make it, they go out of business. The market is competitive, now than the body is hard, an industry (down) is always a small factory, big factory will not fall. "

Lin Haiping thought, no big deal is all lost, to start again. Even back in 1992, he was carving beef at a relative's butcher shop. At that time, beef was sold for 4.5 yuan a catty, and beef balls for 6 yuan a catty. After 16 years, he borrowed money to open a beef shop and had three tables selling hot pot. At that time, he thought that if he could sell 10 catties of beef balls every day, and then sell 10 tables of Hotpot, he would be satisfied.
